Transformer-based AMC¶

This implementation applies R-Transformer architecture for automatic modulation classification, here, the network model has structure as shown below:

structre of RT

If you want to see Python source codes, please click:

https://github.com/louisinhit/transformer_based_AMC.git

Here only tests the performance of this transformer-based network (no train):

Testset is selected evenly from full dataset, original set has 24 26 4096 samples (24 classes, 26 kinds of SNR and 4096 samples each), trainset has 24 26 (4096-512) and testset has 24 26 512 pieces (train : test = 7:1).

The result accuracy curve is posted here first:¶

# functions will be used.

def output_s(message, save_filename):
    print (message)
    with open(save_filename, 'a') as out:
        out.write(message + '\n')

def test(testset):
    model.eval()
    test_loss = 0
    correct = 0
    total = 0
    test_loader = utils.DataLoader(testset, batch_size=32)
    predict = []
    
    with torch.no_grad():
        for data, target in test_loader:
            data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
            output = model(data)
            target = target.squeeze_()
            _, predicted = torch.max(output.data, 1)
            total += target.size(0)
            correct += (predicted == target).sum().item()
            predict.extend(predicted)
        message = ('\nTest set: SNR : {} , Accuracy: {}/{} ({:.3f}%)\n'.format(
            snr, correct, total, 100. * correct / total))
        output_s(message, 'test_cm_array/test_msg.txt')
        return correct / total, predict


def create_label():

    mods = range(24)
    mo = []
    for m in mods:
        mo.append([m] * 4096 * 26)

    mo = np.expand_dims(np.hstack(mo), axis=1)
    print (np.shape(mo))

    snr = []
    for m in range(24):
        for i in range( -20, 32, 2 ):
            snr.append([i] * 4096)

    return mo, np.hstack(snr)


def get_set():

    x = h5py.File("GOLD_XYZ_OSC.0001_1024.hdf5", 'r+')
    labels, snrs = create_label()
    # load the test set idx
    with open('test_idx_all.txt') as f:
        lines = f.read().splitlines()
    test_idx = [int(float(i)) for i in lines]
    
    data_test0 = []
    for it in test_idx:
        data_test0.append(x['X'][it, :, :])
    
    data_test0 = np.asarray(data_test0)
    label_test0 = labels[test_idx, :]
    snr_test = snrs[test_idx]

    return data_test0, label_test0, snr_test

plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"]=10,10
accmat = []

for snr in range( -20, 32, 2 ):
    tidx = list(np.where(snr_test == snr))

    data_test = np.squeeze(data_test0[tidx, :, :], axis=0)
    label_test_y = np.squeeze(label_test0[tidx, :], axis=0)

    data_test = torch.from_numpy(data_test).float()
    label_test = torch.from_numpy(label_test_y).long()

    test_set = utils.TensorDataset(data_test, label_test)
    # estimate classes
    acc, t_predict = test(test_set)
    cr.extend([100 * acc])
    print ('snr %d finished, test acc: %.1f %% \n'  % (snr, 100 * acc))
    
    # F-measure score
    predict = [int(i) for i in t_predict]
    fm.append(list(skm.f1_score(list(np.hstack(label_test_y)), predict, average=None)))
    
    # plot confusion mat
    conf = np.zeros([24,24])
    for i in range(0, label_test_y.shape[0]):
        conf[label_test_y[i],predict[i]] += 1
    # save acc
    accpersnr = []
    for j in range(24):
        accpersnr.extend([float(conf[j,j]/512.0)])
    accmat.append(accpersnr)
    print (accpersnr) 
    #print_mat = pd.DataFrame(conf)
    #print_mat.to_excel(excel_writer = "test_cm_array/conf_mat %d.xlsx" % (snr))    
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(conf,index = cm_idx, columns = cm_idx)
    plt.figure(figsize = (25,25))
    fig = plt.figure()
    sn.heatmap(df_cm, cmap="YlGnBu")
    plt.show()
    fig.savefig('test_CM_pics/confmat %d.jpg' % (snr))
